Brief run-through:

+block

–block




consistent with an anomalously sharp kitchen knife
附加记录：    

The question is: What constitutes an ? Your elaboration of it seems like a stronger version of a knife (that could cut through steel). It might do well to have a clearer (and empirically defined) description of the knife's sharpness.

On that note, what would an invisible kitchen knife need to be so sharp?



Researcher Clarent's work obligations - as tested by Clarent by swinging at the air around her, saying 
附加记录：    

Is this really necessary? It's borderline unprofessional behaviour and there is no indication that 2124-1 can  through abstract concepts (That could be a cool concept to work with though).

Even so, how would cutting the air around oneself cut an abstract concept tied to oneself? It is slightly more logically to be cutting yourself or your brain or something but I digress.

Pros:

Admittedly, this is the first time I see an imaginary knife drawn from a pizza box as though it were a sheath.


Cons:

The  story felt way too convenient. Unless I am mistaken, a researcher's friend just messaged him that he found a potential SCP by chance. This implies unprofessionalism on part of the researcher (a major security compromise) and a level of coincidence that is jarring to believe in. A stronger origin may have been a random civilian accidentally using the SCP. While relatively mundane (and even cliche), it is easier to believe than a researcher's friend calling him about a possible anomalous item.
In the main bulk of the article, you never explicitly explained what SCP-2124 is exactly. I can infer that it is an invisible knife, but it took a while to realise that. It might do well to state SCP-2124-1's existence and what it is, before jumping to casually talking about it and its properties.









